  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is the income requirement so high?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Cayman positions itself as a premium destination. The high threshold ensures residents can afford the cost of living and contribute to the local economy. It also maintains the islands' upscale character.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there really no income tax?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Correct. The Cayman Islands have zero direct taxation: no income tax, capital gains tax, inheritance tax, corporate tax, or sales tax. Government revenue comes from import duties, tourism, and financial services fees.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work for a Cayman company?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The Global Citizen Concierge requires you work remotely for non-Cayman entities. You cannot take local employment. This protects the local job market while allowing remote workers.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does this compare to Bermuda?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Both are premium British territories with zero taxes. Bermuda's program (Work from Bermuda) requires $100k income and costs ~$300/year—cheaper than Cayman's $1,469. Cayman offers warmer weather and better diving; Bermuda is closer to US Northeast.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. The $1,949 couple/family rate includes dependents. Combined household income must be $150,000+. School-age children can attend local schools (private schools available).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the path to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Global Citizen program is separate from residency. Permanent residency in Cayman typically requires substantial investment ($1M+) or employment. The 2-year certificate doesn't automatically lead to residency.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

